      "site": "sfw.mcmorgan.org",
      "slug": "thread-mode",
      "title": "Thread Mode",
      "text": "Thread mode is a form of discussion where our community holds a conversation. It is the beginning of a process of distilling experience that culminates in patterns."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f536e9603adc2787",
      "text": "But dialogue isn't all it's cracked up to be. A lot of Thread Mode work on c2 , Meatball [http://meatballwiki.org/wiki/ wiki], and Weblogs And Wikis Wiki is redundant and monologic. Less a dialogue and more a sequence of loosely related micro-essays or assertions. We acknowledge this when we refactor threads into discourses with the loose ends and remainders refashioned into stubs."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6e64a4167ed629e6",
      "text": "ThreadMode was not intended to be the record of an exchange but a technique of invention. ([[Discussion As Invention]] and maybe something on [[Vygotsky]].) The idea was akin to the brainstorm, with a dose of exploring for stasis and topical arguments. The idea was to collectively voice multiple arguments - not necessarily in support of one's own but to add to the pool of arguments and perspectives that need to be considered. The idea is that once a page - a dissertation - starts to gel, we then have a place to establish stubs, which lead to other perspectives, ideologies, compositions. The vision of the wiki as a collaborative document and workspace comes forward when we can constellate these various dissertations. Rather than embedding a set of possible ideas and arguments in a single page along a thread, we create webs with documents. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "188c92ebf4be4c5e",
      "text": "Participants tended to view ThreadMode as a kind of [[Speaker's Corner]]. We envisioned lots of discussion, leading to a developing document. But the ThreadMode became a loose collection of soapboxes, each speaker addressing a different public. A set of monologues rather than speakers in dialogue. This arrangement can work, but it needs a moderator to synthesize the ideas. Hard work. The moderator has to be both intrusive - not afraid of re-working specific statements - and external to the argument in order to be, um, moderate. Few want the position. Few in the local wiki community want this kind of rhetorical intervention."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b7d0e459ce349a87",
      "text": "One way out of this cul de sac is to rethink thread mode with the understanding that document / dissertation pages can be placed in dialogue with one another. Demote ThreadMode and promote the larger conversation between document or dissertation pages."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "eb6acd27a38c678a",
      "text": "[[Place Dissertation Pages in Dialogue]] or [[Constellate Dissertation Pages]]"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "00893d99d3b3118d",
      "text": "<b>Not much comes of ThreadMode</b> Review the ThreadMode work at Weblogs and Wikis [http://erhetoric.org/WeblogsAndWikis/wikka.php?wakka=HomePage traditional wiki]. You'll see that not a lot of thread mode discussion comes to much, in great part because adding to thread mode becomes a way of avoiding committing to creating a dissertation page.  Students report every semester, \"Doing ThreadMode is just easier!\" The addition to a thread might help the writer think about an idea - but, I'd suggest, so does taking energy to start a dissertation page. Yes, adding to a thread might spur the next person into action, get her thinking about a new idea- but so can a dissertation page."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e30df5206613f1ff",
      "text": "As [[Mike Caulfield]] observes, \"What the disseration does is force me to try and articulate your concerns in summary, and by doing that gain an understanding of your experience. I have to try and write your experience -- I can't just assert mine. We work together instead of in opposition. That produces better discourse -- I have to read your concerns carefully in the thread, because I am going to need to articulate them back to you.\" from [[Is Dissertation Over Discourse Gendered?]]"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "b33751be4a81fc95",
      "text": "<h3>Critique of ThreadMode</h3>"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "ab267c8cb10f5bcf",
      "text": "<b>In practice, ThreadMode encouraged conversation rather than invention</b> TheadMode is taken as an invitation to discussion rather than as an invitation to invention, and threads tend to show the usual patterns of discussions online - patterns that get in the way of developing invention. For instance, One-Person - One-Perspective tends to be foregrounded in threads. This is especially pronounced in students working on the wiki in that they understand their way of thinking as theirs and theirs alone and proclaim that Every Person Has A Different Opinion. The belief gets in the way of seeing patterns in the arguments, and we need patterns to get to DiscourseMode."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b2f37cac69b7b3aa",
      "text": "More socially profound / valuable / significant / knowledge comes of developing things beyond the personal and into the social. The wiki asks uses to develop pages that others can stop by in later semesters and build on further."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "23dc0be19534851b",
      "text": "The matter in composing is where to place and how to use discussion for invention and drafting the collective page."
