    {
      "type": "add",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "c086a2d6c4937686",
        "text": "[[M C Morgan]] Years of watching thread mode discussions go on at Weblogs and Wikis [http://erhetoric.org/WeblogsAndWikis/wikka.php?wakka=HomePage traditional wiki] and the advent of FedWiki as a distributed system has encouraged me to re-think the old ThreadMode into DocumentMode pattern of composing. I've always viewed ThreadMode is an inventional technique - a way of locating and trying out the ways that an idea might be constructed and a document composed. Once a document - a dissertation - starts to gel, we then have a place to anchor stubs, which lead to other perspectives, ideologies, compositions. The real vision of the wiki comes forward when we can constellate these various dissertations. Rather than embedding a set of possible ideas and arguments in a single page along a thread, we can, with documents, create webs."
      },
      "id": "c086a2d6c4937686",
      "date": 1426181987096
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "cca6d9e24d1474aa",
        "text": "I'm not sure FedWiki supports multiparty discussion well. Traditional wiki only kinda supports it using delimiters and a style guide, and perhaps FedWiki will develop similar indicators of processes. But a dedicated discussion space might support thread mode better than the wiki page. Wikipedia has talk pages. The thread mode is near by but separate from the dissertation, which makes the dissertation more useful to readers and makes the thread mode more useful to writers. \"Useful\" meaning it facilitates creating a better crafted dissertation mode, one that can be woven in more to the overall net. "
      },
      "after": "c086a2d6c4937686",
      "id": "cca6d9e24d1474aa",
      "date": 1426181992889
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "ab267c8cb10f5bcf",
        "text": "The other idea I'm resisting is the idea if One-Person - One-Perspective that tends to be foregrounded in threads. This is especially pronounced in students working on the wiki in that they understand their way of thinking as theirs and theirs alone (not so), and proclaim Every Person Has A Different Opinion (also not so). I'm of the mind (the ideology) that more socially profound / valuable / significant / knowledge comes of developing things beyond the personal. It's that kind of stuff I'm always asking students to aspire to on the wiki, so that others can stop by in later semesters and build on it further."
      },
      "after": "cca6d9e24d1474aa",
      "id": "ab267c8cb10f5bcf",
